Brief Communication

Published: 10 March 2026

Thermal discomfort in urban underground metro systems
                    Giorgia Chinazzo 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0003-0842-84931 & Alessandro F. Rotta Loria 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0001-6584-75262

Nature Cities

(2026)Cite this article

Subjects

            Civil engineeringEnvironmental healthEnvironmental studies

AbstractMillions of people use urban underground spaces daily, yet their subjective thermal comfort during commuting remains poorly quantified. Here, analyzing over 85,000 crowdsourced posts from commuters in Boston, London and New York, this study reveals widespread thermal discomfort in metro systems, with recurrent peaks by hour, day of the week, and season. These findings can help policymakers and transit operators better anticipate, mitigate and adapt to the unwanted effects of extreme heat in urban underground environments.

